1
00:00:12,179 --> 00:00:14,181
<i>TYSON".
Must we die?</i>

2
00:00:16,558 --> 00:00:20,608
<i>Are there beings in the cosmos
who live forever...</i>

3
00:00:21,897 --> 00:00:26,619
<i>...afloat on an endless journey
down the river of time?</i>

4
00:02:05,709 --> 00:02:11,011
<i>TYSON: Our ancestors marked the passage
of time by the moon and stars.</i>

5
00:02:39,618 --> 00:02:43,464
But it was the people who once
lived here, around 5000 years ago...

6
00:02:43,622 --> 00:02:47,752
...who first started chopping up time into
smaller bite-sized portions of hours...

7
00:02:47,918 --> 00:02:54,346
...and minutes. They call
this place Uruk. We call it Iraq.

8
00:02:54,925 --> 00:02:56,347
It's a part of Mesopotamia...

9
00:02:56,510 --> 00:03:00,390
...the land between the Tigris
and the Euphrates rivers.

10
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:05,194
The city was invented here.

11
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:07,889
And one of humanity's
greatest victories was

12
00:03:07,901 --> 00:03:10,449
won in the ceaseless
battle against time.

13
00:03:10,607 --> 00:03:13,611
It was here that we learned
how to write.

14
00:03:13,777 --> 00:03:15,779
Death could no longer silence us.

15
00:03:15,946 --> 00:03:19,450
And writing gave us the power
to reach across the millennia...

16
00:03:19,616 --> 00:03:22,415
...and speak inside
the heads of the living.

17
00:03:23,036 --> 00:03:26,666
<i>No one had ever spoken across
a longer stretch of time's river...</i>

18
00:03:26,832 --> 00:03:30,962
<i>...than this Akkadian princess,
daughter of the first emperor in history...</i>

19
00:03:31,128 --> 00:03:34,428
<i>...and priestess of the moon. Enheduanna.</i>

20
00:03:34,589 --> 00:03:36,591
<i>For not only did she write poetry...</i>

21
00:03:36,758 --> 00:03:40,513
<i>...but Enheduanna did something
no one before her had ever done.</i>

22
00:03:40,679 --> 00:03:43,478
<i>She signed her name to her work.</i>

23
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:49,397
<i>She's the first person for whom we can say
we know who she was and what she dreamed.</i>

24
00:03:49,563 --> 00:03:54,194
<i>She dreamt of stepping through
the Gate of Wonder.</i>

25
00:03:54,359 --> 00:03:59,536
<i>Here's a thought Enheduanna
sent across more than 4000 years to you.</i>

26
00:03:59,698 --> 00:04:03,828
<i>It's from her work entitled
Lady oi the Largest Heart.</i>

27
00:04:04,536 --> 00:04:06,538
[SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

28
00:04:08,373 --> 00:04:12,753
<i>ENHEDUANNA". Innana, the planet Venus,
goddess of love...</i>

29
00:04:12,919 --> 00:04:17,390
<i>...will have a great destiny
throughout the entire universe.</i>

30
00:04:17,549 --> 00:04:19,972
<i>Throughout the entire universe.</i>

31
00:04:20,135 --> 00:04:22,939
And Uruk is also the place
where the epic tale

32
00:04:22,951 --> 00:04:25,767
of the hero's journey
was first written down.

33
00:04:25,932 --> 00:04:30,859
Before Batman, Luke Skywalker,
Odysseus, before them all...

34
00:04:31,021 --> 00:04:36,653
...there was a man named Gilgamesh
who left home on a quest to vanquish time.

35
00:04:37,569 --> 00:04:40,698
<i>Gilgamesh was searching for immortality.</i>

36
00:04:40,864 --> 00:04:44,539
<i>He looked everywhere,
gained complete wisdom...</i>

37
00:04:45,285 --> 00:04:47,253
<i>...uncovered what was hidden.</i>

38
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:51,007
<i>He brought back a tale of times
before the Great Flood.</i>

39
00:04:51,166 --> 00:04:52,213
[ROARING]

40
00:04:52,709 --> 00:04:57,715
<i>He built the wall of Uruk,
which no future king will ever match.</i>

41
00:04:57,881 --> 00:05:02,762
<i>Read the story of that man, Gilgamesh,
a hero born of Uruk...</i>

42
00:05:02,928 --> 00:05:05,556
<i>...who went through all
kinds of sufferings...</i>

43
00:05:05,722 --> 00:05:08,066
<i>...who crossed the ocean, the broad seas...</i>

44
00:05:08,225 --> 00:05:10,193
<i>...as far as the sunrise...</i>

45
00:05:10,352 --> 00:05:14,482
<i>...who inspected the edges of the world,
searching for eternal life.</i>

46
00:05:14,648 --> 00:05:19,404
<i>On his travels, Gilgamesh encountered
a wise man named Utnapishtim...</i>

47
00:05:19,569 --> 00:05:22,914
<i>...who told him the story of a flood
that destroyed the world...</i>

48
00:05:23,073 --> 00:05:26,077
<i>...and how one of the gods
instructed Utnapishtim...</i>

49
00:05:26,243 --> 00:05:30,794
<i>...to build an ark
to rescue his family and the animals.</i>

50
00:06:03,321 --> 00:06:08,418
The earliest surviving account of the flood
legend was written down in Mesopotamia...

51
00:06:08,577 --> 00:06:13,925
...a thousand years before it was retold
as the story of Noah in the Old Testament.

52
00:06:14,082 --> 00:06:18,383
So you could say Gilgamesh
fulfilled his quest for immortality.

53
00:06:18,545 --> 00:06:22,675
We still read the <i>Epic</i> of <i>Gilgamesh,</i>
and with every reader...

54
00:06:22,841 --> 00:06:24,138
...he lives again.

55
00:06:24,301 --> 00:06:29,478
And all those heroes and superheroes who
have come since follow in the footsteps...

56
00:06:29,639 --> 00:06:31,812
...of the first hero's journey...

57
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:34,478
...another kind of immortality.

58
00:06:34,644 --> 00:06:40,151
A story sent from one civilization
to another across thousands of years.

59
00:06:40,317 --> 00:06:44,663
But life itself sends its own stories
across billions of years.

60
00:06:48,825 --> 00:06:52,170
It's a message that every one of us
carries inside...

61
00:06:52,329 --> 00:06:55,469
...inscribed in all the
cells of our bodies in

62
00:06:55,481 --> 00:06:58,632
a language that all
life on Earth can read.

63
00:06:58,793 --> 00:07:03,549
The genetic code is written in an alphabet
consisting of only four letters.

64
00:07:03,715 --> 00:07:09,813
Each letter is a molecule made of atoms.
Each word is three letters long.

65
00:07:09,971 --> 00:07:13,191
Every living thing
is a masterpiece...

66
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:16,650
...written by nature
and edited by evolution.

67
00:07:16,811 --> 00:07:18,358
The instructions for running...

68
00:07:18,521 --> 00:07:21,525
...and reproducing
the intricate machinery of life.

69
00:07:22,150 --> 00:07:24,619
The essential message of life
has been copied...

70
00:07:24,778 --> 00:07:28,203
...and recopied
for more than 3 billion years.

71
00:07:28,365 --> 00:07:30,743
But where did that message
come from?

72
00:07:30,909 --> 00:07:32,627
Nobody knows.

73
00:07:42,170 --> 00:07:44,423
Perhaps it began in a shallow,
sunlit pool...

74
00:07:44,589 --> 00:07:46,057
...just like this.

75
00:07:46,216 --> 00:07:52,394
Somehow, carbon-rich molecules began using
energy to make crude copies of themselves.

76
00:07:52,555 --> 00:07:56,685
Some varieties were better
at making copies, and left more offspring.

77
00:07:56,851 --> 00:08:00,230
The competing molecules
became more elaborate.

78
00:08:00,397 --> 00:08:03,742
Evolution and life itself
was underway.

79
00:08:07,070 --> 00:08:10,460
<i>Or life could've started
in the searing heat</i>

80
00:08:10,472 --> 00:08:13,874
<i>of a volcanic vent on
the deep sea floor.</i>

81
00:08:17,789 --> 00:08:22,010
<i>Or is it possible that life came to Earth
as a hitchhiker?</i>

82
00:08:22,544 --> 00:08:27,641
<i>Let me tell you a story about a traveler
from another world.</i>

83
00:08:32,595 --> 00:08:36,600
<i>The peace of the Egyptian village
of Nakhla, near Alexandria...</i>

84
00:08:36,766 --> 00:08:40,816
<i>...was abruptly shattered
on a June morning in 1911.</i>

85
00:08:54,784 --> 00:08:58,914
<i>Written in this meteorite
was a message from another planet.</i>

86
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:03,711
<i>But 70 years would pass
before anyone could read it.</i>

87
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:12,644
<i>In 1976, NASA landed two Viking
spacecraft on Mars.</i>

88
00:09:12,802 --> 00:09:17,933
<i>Carl Sagan took us there on our original
journey through the cosmos.</i>

89
00:09:18,099 --> 00:09:22,149
SAGAN: <i>We found that the Martian air
was less than 1 percent as dense as ours...</i>

90
00:09:22,312 --> 00:09:25,156
<i>...and made mostly of carbon dioxide.</i>

91
00:09:25,315 --> 00:09:30,492
<i>There were smaller amounts of nitrogen,
argon, water vapor and oxygen.</i>

92
00:09:31,321 --> 00:09:34,666
<i>TYSON: A few years later, when scientists
thought to analyze the gasses...</i>

93
00:09:34,824 --> 00:09:38,749
<i>...trapped inside the Nakhia meteorite,
and other members of its class...</i>

94
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:42,007
<i>...they found a striking similarity.</i>

95
00:09:42,165 --> 00:09:45,760
<i>The vast majority of meteorites
are fragments of asteroids.</i>

96
00:09:45,919 --> 00:09:51,517
<i>But the kind that hit Nakhla on Earth
could only have come from one place.</i>

97
00:10:02,811 --> 00:10:04,233
Mars.

98
00:10:09,025 --> 00:10:11,869
TYSON:
Welcome to Mars.

99
00:10:16,574 --> 00:10:19,498
Over a billion years ago,
a volcano erupted here...

100
00:10:19,661 --> 00:10:22,540
...and its lava cooled into solid rock.

101
00:10:22,705 --> 00:10:27,131
Hundreds of millions of years later,
this area was flooded with water.

102
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:31,389
And long after that flood, an asteroid
the size of the Rock of Gibraltar...

103
00:10:31,548 --> 00:10:36,349
...crashed into the Martian surface,
blasting out a huge crater.

104
00:10:39,264 --> 00:10:42,689
Much of the debris
was ejected back out into space...

105
00:10:42,851 --> 00:10:45,012
...where it orbited
the sun until a

106
00:10:45,024 --> 00:10:47,197
gravitational tug from
its home planet, Mars...

107
00:10:47,355 --> 00:10:52,987
...diverted one of the boulders into a
collision course with Earth. Its arrival...

108
00:10:53,153 --> 00:10:56,407
...shook up the little village
of Nakhla. Meteorites...

109
00:10:56,573 --> 00:10:58,325
...of the type that hit Nakhla...

110
00:10:58,491 --> 00:11:02,371
...are the vehicles of a natural
interplanetary transit system...

111
00:11:02,537 --> 00:11:04,881
...that sends rocks between the planets.

112
00:11:05,832 --> 00:11:09,507
<i>Such a meteorite can safely shelter
microscopic cargo...</i>

113
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:14,266
...the seeds of life,
an interplanetary ark.

114
00:11:14,424 --> 00:11:17,803
Most rocks are porous,
full of tiny nooks and crannies...

115
00:11:17,969 --> 00:11:20,267
...where life can stow away.

116
00:11:24,184 --> 00:11:28,940
<i>We know that some microbes can survive
the hostile environment of space.</i>

117
00:11:29,105 --> 00:11:31,608
<i>Take these guys, for instance.</i>

118
00:11:31,774 --> 00:11:35,574
<i>These microbes spent a year and a half
riding on the outside...</i>

119
00:11:35,737 --> 00:11:40,243
<i>...of the International Space Station,
exposed to the extreme temperatures...</i>

120
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:43,127
<i>...vacuum, and radiation of space.</i>

121
00:11:43,286 --> 00:11:45,948
<i>And some of them were
still alive and kicking</i>

122
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:48,634
<i>when they were brought
back to Earth.</i>

123
00:11:48,791 --> 00:11:51,510
<i>Even more astonishing
are these creatures...</i>

124
00:11:51,669 --> 00:11:56,266
<i>...awakened from a death-like sleep
of 8 million years.</i>

125
00:11:56,424 --> 00:11:59,479
<i>They were frozen in the
Antarctic ice millions</i>

126
00:11:59,491 --> 00:12:02,557
<i>of years before our
species even existed.</i>

127
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:04,315
And they're still alive.

128
00:12:06,434 --> 00:12:11,235
If life can withstand the hardships
of space and endure for millennia...

129
00:12:11,397 --> 00:12:13,849
...then it could ride the
natural interplanetary

130
00:12:13,861 --> 00:12:16,324
transit system from
world to world.

131
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:20,832
It's a good bet that our microbial
ancestors spent some time in space.

132
00:12:20,990 --> 00:12:22,537
Why do we think so?

133
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:26,000
The Earth is 4 and a half billion
years old.

134
00:12:28,665 --> 00:12:30,667
<i>For the first half of its lifetime...</i>

135
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:35,634
<i>...large asteroids were bombarding
the planet every few million years.</i>

136
00:12:36,506 --> 00:12:42,684
<i>The most violent impacts vaporized the
oceans and even melted the surface rock.</i>

137
00:12:42,845 --> 00:12:46,025
<i>Each such collision
would have completely</i>

138
00:12:46,037 --> 00:12:49,228
<i>sterilized the planet
for thousands of years.</i>

139
00:12:50,853 --> 00:12:55,324
<i>But we know from fossils in the rocks
that bacteria were evolving on Earth...</i>

140
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:57,861
<i>...during this formative period.</i>

141
00:12:59,362 --> 00:13:04,619
<i>So how could life have survived
such a lethal series of blows?</i>

142
00:13:05,702 --> 00:13:08,171
Whenever one of those big asteroids
hit the Earth...

143
00:13:08,329 --> 00:13:13,506
...the explosion would blast out a crater,
launching millions of boulders into space.

144
00:13:14,168 --> 00:13:17,342
Many of those rocks
carried living bacteria inside.

145
00:13:17,505 --> 00:13:19,883
Some of the bugs
would have survived in space...

146
00:13:20,049 --> 00:13:23,644
...while all those left behind on Earth
would have been fried.

147
00:13:23,803 --> 00:13:26,226
<i>A few thousand years after each impact...</i>

148
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:31,361
<i>...the Earth would have cooled down enough
for water to condense into oceans.</i>

149
00:13:32,186 --> 00:13:35,065
<i>The planet would again be habitable.</i>

150
00:13:35,231 --> 00:13:41,910
Meanwhile, most of the rocks launched into
space would have been orbiting the sun.

151
00:13:42,572 --> 00:13:45,701
<i>Some of them would encounter
the Earth again...</i>

152
00:13:45,867 --> 00:13:47,869
<i>...reenter the atmosphere as meteorites...</i>

153
00:13:48,036 --> 00:13:52,917
<i>...and deliver their precious cargo of life
to re-seed the planet...</i>

154
00:13:54,917 --> 00:13:56,840
<i>...like Noah's ark.</i>

155
00:13:57,003 --> 00:14:00,257
<i>What this means is that life
doesn't have to start over again...</i>

156
00:14:00,423 --> 00:14:03,597
<i>...from scratch after each catastrophe.</i>

157
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:06,764
<i>It can pick up where it left off.</i>

158
00:14:06,929 --> 00:14:08,977
When the solar system
was young...

159
00:14:09,140 --> 00:14:14,738
...Venus was probably more like Earth,
with oceans and maybe even life.

160
00:14:14,896 --> 00:14:18,116
Venus, Earth, and Mars were all
exchanging rocks with each other...

161
00:14:18,274 --> 00:14:20,072
...due to asteroid impacts.

162
00:14:20,234 --> 00:14:24,114
Does life on Earth carry any traces
of interplanetary voyages...

163
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:25,953
...made in the distant past?

164
00:14:26,115 --> 00:14:32,122
Why is it that some microbes can survive
the intense radiation and vacuum of space?

165
00:14:32,288 --> 00:14:35,462
These conditions don't naturally exist
on Earth.

166
00:14:35,625 --> 00:14:39,425
Maybe those bugs are telling us
that their ancestors survived...

167
00:14:39,587 --> 00:14:43,967
...those same conditions in space,
a few billion years ago.

168
00:14:45,093 --> 00:14:48,768
So we know that microbes can stow away
in rocks and survive the voyage...

169
00:14:48,930 --> 00:14:50,557
...from planet to planet.

170
00:14:50,723 --> 00:14:55,820
But what about a trip from star to star,
an interstellar odyssey?

171
00:15:03,820 --> 00:15:05,663
The dandelion.

172
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:08,408
Around 30 million years ago...

173
00:15:08,574 --> 00:15:14,957
...it evolved another way to send its
own message of life through space and time.

174
00:15:22,130 --> 00:15:26,351
<i>Each seedling is a little paratrooper,
floating on the wind...</i>

175
00:15:26,509 --> 00:15:30,013
<i>...risking everything for
a safe place to land.</i>

176
00:15:30,972 --> 00:15:34,567
<i>Updrafts can carry them
higher into the air.</i>

177
00:15:34,725 --> 00:15:36,648
<i>A dandelion can travel dozens...</i>

178
00:15:36,811 --> 00:15:38,859
<i>...possibly hundreds of kilometers...</i>

179
00:15:39,021 --> 00:15:41,365
<i>...even crossing over mountain ranges.</i>

180
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:46,780
<i>Evolution has shaped it
into an exquisite flying machine.</i>

181
00:15:48,114 --> 00:15:50,583
The seed is another kind of ark...

182
00:15:50,741 --> 00:15:53,215
...ensuring the survival
of its species by riding

183
00:15:53,227 --> 00:15:55,713
the currents of the
atmosphere to safe harbors.

184
00:15:55,872 --> 00:15:59,718
Each seed, in its DNA,
carries a story...

185
00:15:59,876 --> 00:16:02,720
...the character and destiny
of the next dandelion.

186
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:07,225
Life propagates by retelling its story.

187
00:16:08,551 --> 00:16:13,398
<i>Is it possible that life could survive
the journey from star to star?</i>

188
00:16:13,556 --> 00:16:19,154
The stars are about a million times farther
apart from each other than are the planets.

189
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:22,537
Space is so vast that
it would take billions

190
00:16:22,549 --> 00:16:25,786
of years for a rock
ejected from the Earth...

191
00:16:25,943 --> 00:16:29,413
<i>...to collide with a planet
circling another star.</i>

192
00:16:29,572 --> 00:16:35,124
Any stowaway microbes would never survive
the cosmic radiation for that long.

193
00:16:35,286 --> 00:16:37,925
But there's a plausible
scenario for how life

194
00:16:37,937 --> 00:16:40,588
could spread from one
solar system to another.

195
00:16:46,464 --> 00:16:49,513
<i>The stars of the Milky Way are drawn
by gravity...</i>

196
00:16:49,675 --> 00:16:53,054
<i>...in their own enormous orbits
around its center.</i>

197
00:16:53,221 --> 00:16:54,564
<i>Our sun, for example...</i>

198
00:16:54,722 --> 00:17:00,229
<i>...takes some 225 million years
to complete a single orbit.</i>

199
00:17:00,394 --> 00:17:02,738
<i>During each revolution around the galaxy...</i>

200
00:17:02,897 --> 00:17:08,154
<i>...our solar system will pass through two
or three gigantic interstellar clouds...</i>

201
00:17:08,319 --> 00:17:11,869
<i>...each of them many light-years across.</i>

202
00:17:15,368 --> 00:17:19,544
<i>Galaxies are world-making machines.</i>

203
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:23,255
<i>Our Milky Way has more than 100
of these vast clouds...</i>

204
00:17:23,417 --> 00:17:28,969
<i>...places where gas and dust condense
to form new stars and planets.</i>

205
00:17:32,009 --> 00:17:34,137
<i>In its travels through the Milky Way...</i>

206
00:17:34,303 --> 00:17:37,557
<i>...our sun is accompanied
not only by its planets...</i>

207
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:41,478
<i>...but also by a trillion distant comets.</i>

208
00:17:42,520 --> 00:17:46,491
<i>When our solar system
passes through an interstellar cloud...</i>

209
00:17:46,649 --> 00:17:51,621
<i>...the gravity of the massive cloud
stirs up the outermost comets.</i>

210
00:17:52,238 --> 00:17:57,995
<i>Some comets will be hurled out
into the space between the stars.</i>

211
00:17:59,203 --> 00:18:02,252
<i>Others will plunge inward...</i>

212
00:18:05,001 --> 00:18:07,504
<i>...falling towards the sun.</i>

213
00:18:22,768 --> 00:18:27,069
<i>And some of them
may collide with the planets.</i>

214
00:18:27,690 --> 00:18:31,035
<i>The high-speed impact of a comet
with a rocky planet...</i>

215
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:34,493
<i>...will launch boulders
like rockets into space.</i>

216
00:18:34,655 --> 00:18:37,204
<i>If that planet should happen
to be inhabited...</i>

217
00:18:37,366 --> 00:18:40,119
<i>...many of those rocks
will carry passengers...</i>

218
00:18:40,286 --> 00:18:42,380
<i>...living microbes.</i>

219
00:18:42,538 --> 00:18:44,461
<i>After thousands of years...</i>

220
00:18:44,624 --> 00:18:48,629
<i>...fragments of the rocks ejected
from Earth can fall as meteors...</i>

221
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:53,891
<i>...into the atmospheres of newborn planets
