225
00:19:13,653 --> 00:19:15,997
The sun emerges from the cloud...

226
00:19:16,155 --> 00:19:21,207
...having scattered the seeds of life
among the newborn worlds of other stars.

227
00:19:21,369 --> 00:19:24,418
Those new worlds, now touched by life...

228
00:19:24,580 --> 00:19:28,175
...will then leave their birth cloud
and go their separate ways.

229
00:19:28,334 --> 00:19:32,931
Eventually, their stars will carry them
through other interstellar clouds...

230
00:19:33,089 --> 00:19:36,969
...where they may seed
still more new worlds.

231
00:19:37,134 --> 00:19:41,230
<i>Imagine this process repeated
from world to world...</i>

232
00:19:41,389 --> 00:19:45,439
<i>...each one bringing life to others.</i>

233
00:19:50,606 --> 00:19:54,827
Life would then propagate,
like a slow chain reaction...

234
00:19:55,778 --> 00:19:56,870
...through the entire galaxy.

235
00:20:01,701 --> 00:20:05,877
<i>This could be how life came to Earth.</i>

236
00:20:06,038 --> 00:20:07,631
<i>We do not know for sure.</i>

237
00:20:07,790 --> 00:20:11,010
Are there any beings out there like us?

238
00:20:11,168 --> 00:20:15,218
Do they ask the same questions?
Do they share our fears?

239
00:20:15,381 --> 00:20:18,430
Do they have heroes and adventurers?

240
00:20:18,592 --> 00:20:20,435
[BELL TOLLING]

241
00:20:23,764 --> 00:20:27,359
If they do exist, where are they?

242
00:20:27,518 --> 00:20:30,488
How might they make
their presence known?

243
00:20:45,911 --> 00:20:49,836
How did we first announce our presence
to the galaxy?

244
00:20:49,999 --> 00:20:55,506
It was 1946, the year after
the Second World War ended.

245
00:20:58,424 --> 00:21:02,019
ANNOUNCER: <i>The imaginations of H. G. Wells
and Buck Rogers never cooked</i> up...

246
00:21:02,178 --> 00:21:03,725
<i>...a more fantastic experience...</i>

247
00:21:03,929 --> 00:21:08,025
<i>...than the Army engineers
at their laboratory in Belmar, New Jersey.</i>

248
00:21:08,184 --> 00:21:11,905
<i>It opens up unlimited possibilities
for interstellar experiment.</i>

249
00:21:12,062 --> 00:21:15,908
<i>TYSON". American engineers bounced
a beam of radio waves off the moon...</i>

250
00:21:16,066 --> 00:21:19,195
<i>...and were able to detect its echo.</i>

251
00:21:19,987 --> 00:21:21,580
[THUMPING]

252
00:21:24,533 --> 00:21:27,707
<i>They called this experiment Project Diana.</i>

253
00:21:27,870 --> 00:21:33,092
<i>It was the first interstellar message
ever sent by our species.</i>

254
00:21:33,959 --> 00:21:35,552
<i>An eerie tolling bell.</i>

255
00:21:35,711 --> 00:21:37,054
[BELL TOLLING]

256
00:21:38,214 --> 00:21:41,309
If one allows the imagination free rein...

257
00:21:41,467 --> 00:21:45,597
...many future possibilities appear.

258
00:21:46,639 --> 00:21:51,645
Spaceships, carrying passengers
at thousands of miles per hour...

259
00:21:51,811 --> 00:21:53,233
...can be controlled...

260
00:21:53,395 --> 00:21:56,945
...and communication established
with their passengers.

261
00:21:57,107 --> 00:22:01,954
For we now know that the
Earth's atmosphere can be penetrated.

262
00:22:07,159 --> 00:22:08,911
<i>TYSON".
Traveling at the speed of light...</i>

263
00:22:09,078 --> 00:22:13,003
<i>...it takes just over one second for a
radio wave to reach the lunar surface.</i>

264
00:22:14,500 --> 00:22:18,425
<i>But the expanding wave front
is much bigger than the moon.</i>

265
00:22:18,587 --> 00:22:21,261
<i>Most of the wave passes right by</i> it...

266
00:22:21,423 --> 00:22:24,552
<i>...but the central part gets bounced back.</i>

267
00:22:25,261 --> 00:22:29,687
<i>After a round-trip travel time of two
and a half seconds, it hits our planet.</i>

268
00:22:31,183 --> 00:22:34,904
<i>Project Diana transmitted
a series of powerful radio waves...</i>

269
00:22:35,062 --> 00:22:37,611
<i>...one every four seconds,
to ping the moon.</i>

270
00:22:37,773 --> 00:22:39,446
[BELL TOLLING]

271
00:22:40,734 --> 00:22:44,864
<i>The parts that missed the moon
are traveling still.</i>

272
00:22:47,116 --> 00:22:48,959
<i>It was just the beginning.</i>

273
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:50,461
<i>After World War H...</i>

274
00:22:50,619 --> 00:22:53,668
<i>"television stations cropped up
all over the United States...</i>

275
00:22:53,831 --> 00:22:56,425
<i>...and other parts of the world.</i>

276
00:22:56,584 --> 00:22:58,131
<i>The Project Diana message...</i>

277
00:22:58,294 --> 00:23:02,470
<i>...and the FM radio, television
and radar signals of the 20th century...</i>

278
00:23:02,631 --> 00:23:05,475
<i>...all move outward at the speed of light.</i>

279
00:23:05,634 --> 00:23:09,309
<i>These transmissions make up
a vast sphere of radio waves...</i>

280
00:23:09,471 --> 00:23:12,645
<i>...expanding away from the Earth
in all directions.</i>

281
00:23:12,808 --> 00:23:17,484
<i>You could say that
our world is radiating stories.</i>

282
00:23:17,646 --> 00:23:22,152
<i>Our ancestors etched the story
of Gilgamesh into clay tablets...</i>

283
00:23:22,318 --> 00:23:24,992
<i>...sending that epic tale into the future.</i>

284
00:23:25,154 --> 00:23:30,627
<i>We've encoded our stories in radio waves
and beamed them into space.</i>

285
00:23:30,784 --> 00:23:32,912
<i>They cover one light-year of distance...</i>

286
00:23:33,078 --> 00:23:37,879
<i>...that's 6 trillion miles, for every
year of time since they were sent.</i>

287
00:23:38,042 --> 00:23:41,797
<i>We've been sending our stories into space
for over 70 years.</i>

288
00:23:41,962 --> 00:23:44,841
<i>The leading edge of these signals
has already washed over...</i>

289
00:23:45,007 --> 00:23:48,056
<i>...thousands of planets of other stars.</i>

290
00:23:48,218 --> 00:23:52,314
<i>If any of these worlds are home
to a civilization with radio telescopes...</i>

291
00:23:52,473 --> 00:23:56,194
<i>...they could already know that we're here.</i>

292
00:23:59,104 --> 00:24:03,701
<i>What if other worlds
are sending their stories into space?</i>

293
00:24:04,276 --> 00:24:09,032
<i>Since 1960, we've been listening
for extraterrestrial radio signals...</i>

294
00:24:09,198 --> 00:24:12,702
<i>...without hearing so
much as a tolling bell.</i>

295
00:24:12,868 --> 00:24:18,045
<i>But our search has been sporadic
and limited to certain parts of the sky.</i>

296
00:24:22,586 --> 00:24:26,466
<i>For all we know,
we may have just missed an alien signal...</i>

297
00:24:26,632 --> 00:24:30,227
<i>...looking in the wrong
place at the wrong time.</i>

298
00:24:30,386 --> 00:24:34,141
<i>We've only listened to a miniscule fraction
of the stars in our galaxy.</i>

299
00:24:34,306 --> 00:24:36,149
<i>And there may be another problem.</i>

300
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:39,983
<i>We are, to some extent, prisoners
of our own moment in time...</i>

301
00:24:40,145 --> 00:24:42,318
<i>...and the limits of our technology.</i>

302
00:24:42,481 --> 00:24:44,529
<i>Radio and television broadcasting...</i>

303
00:24:44,692 --> 00:24:48,196
<i>...may be only a brief passing phase
in our technological development.</i>

304
00:24:49,571 --> 00:24:52,062
<i>When we imagine
alien civilizations</i>

305
00:24:52,074 --> 00:24:54,577
<i>broadcasting signals
with radio telescopes...</i>

306
00:24:54,743 --> 00:24:57,587
<i>...are we any different
from earlier generations...</i>

307
00:24:57,746 --> 00:25:01,751
<i>...who imagined riding cannon shells
to the moon?</i>

308
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:05,846
<i>Civilizations even slightly
more advanced than ours...</i>

309
00:25:06,005 --> 00:25:09,760
<i>...may have already moved on
to some other mode of communication...</i>

310
00:25:09,925 --> 00:25:13,429
<i>...one that we have yet to discover
or even imagine.</i>

311
00:25:13,595 --> 00:25:17,395
<i>Their messages could be swirling all
around us at this very moment...</i>

312
00:25:17,558 --> 00:25:20,607
<i>...but we lack the means
to perceive them...</i>

313
00:25:20,769 --> 00:25:24,273
<i>...just as all of our ancestors,
up to a little more than a century ago...</i>

314
00:25:24,440 --> 00:25:29,742
<i>...would have been oblivious to the most
urgent radio signal from another world.</i>

315
00:25:30,571 --> 00:25:33,620
<i>But there's another, more
troubling possibility.</i>

316
00:25:33,782 --> 00:25:36,376
<i>Civilizations, like other living things...</i>

317
00:25:36,535 --> 00:25:40,415
<i>...may only live so long
before perishing due to natural causes...</i>

318
00:25:40,581 --> 00:25:43,926
<i>...or violence, or self-inflicted wounds.</i>

319
00:25:44,084 --> 00:25:47,805
<i>Whether or not we ever make contact
with intelligent alien life...</i>

320
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:50,512
<i>...may depend on a critical question:</i>

321
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:54,975
<i>What is the life expectancy
of a civilization?</i>

322
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:22,336
<i>TYSON: By the time of Enheduanna, the first
person to ever get a writing credit...</i>

323
00:26:22,498 --> 00:26:25,468
<i>...civilization was already
more than 1000 years old.</i>

324
00:26:27,628 --> 00:26:31,804
But today, her glorious city
is a barren wasteland.

325
00:26:31,965 --> 00:26:33,137
What went wrong?

326
00:26:33,300 --> 00:26:35,416
One problem was the
almost ceaseless warfare

327
00:26:35,428 --> 00:26:37,555
between the cities
of Mesopotamia...

328
00:26:37,721 --> 00:26:40,520
...which continually destroyed
their achievements.

329
00:26:40,682 --> 00:26:44,528
They glorified military conquest,
and ultimately...

330
00:26:44,686 --> 00:26:47,030
...became its victims.

331
00:26:49,024 --> 00:26:50,822
<i>Another cause of decline was that...</i>

332
00:26:50,984 --> 00:26:54,705
<i>...their technical know-how
overran their understanding of nature.</i>

333
00:26:54,863 --> 00:26:56,536
<i>The ingenious irrigation system...</i>

334
00:26:56,698 --> 00:26:59,872
<i>...that was the basis for the great
civilizations of Mesopotamia...</i>

335
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:02,379
<i>...had an unintended consequence.</i>

336
00:27:02,538 --> 00:27:05,462
<i>The water channeled
into their farmlands every year...</i>

337
00:27:05,624 --> 00:27:08,924
<i>...evaporated and left its salt behind.</i>

338
00:27:09,086 --> 00:27:13,592
<i>Over generations, the salt accumulated
and began to kill the crops.</i>

339
00:27:13,757 --> 00:27:16,385
<i>And then, about 2200 B.C...</i>

340
00:27:16,552 --> 00:27:19,977
<i>...not long after the time of Enheduanna,
disaster struck.</i>

341
00:27:20,848 --> 00:27:25,228
<i>A drought of truly epic proportions,
lasting for many decades.</i>

342
00:27:25,394 --> 00:27:29,740
<i>The rains stopped, crops withered,
there was famine and anarchy.</i>

343
00:27:29,898 --> 00:27:31,366
<i>Barbarians invaded.</i>

344
00:27:31,525 --> 00:27:34,495
<i>The streets of many cities
were littered with dead.</i>

345
00:27:34,653 --> 00:27:36,872
<i>There could be only one explanation.</i>

346
00:27:37,030 --> 00:27:39,749
<i>Enlil, the supreme god, was angry...</i>

347
00:27:39,908 --> 00:27:42,707
<i>...because one of his temples
had been destroyed.</i>

348
00:27:42,870 --> 00:27:45,339
<i>The people of Mesopotamia could not know...</i>

349
00:27:45,497 --> 00:27:49,593
<i>...that the same drought was crushing
the dawning civilizations of Egypt...</i>

350
00:27:49,751 --> 00:27:53,051
<i>...Greece, India, Pakistan and China.</i>

351
00:27:53,213 --> 00:27:57,434
<i>All the gods of the Earth must have
been really angry about something.</i>

352
00:27:57,593 --> 00:27:58,970
<i>For all their brilliance...</i>

353
00:27:59,136 --> 00:28:01,935
<i>...the people of those civilizations
had no inkling...</i>

354
00:28:02,097 --> 00:28:06,273
<i>...they were experiencing
abrupt climate change.</i>

355
00:28:08,937 --> 00:28:10,689
<i>Three thousand years later...</i>

356
00:28:10,856 --> 00:28:14,406
<i>...the climate would change abruptly
for another glorious civilization...</i>

357
00:28:14,568 --> 00:28:16,411
<i>...this one in Central America.</i>

358
00:28:16,570 --> 00:28:19,949
<i>At its peak,
the Mayan civilization perished...</i>

359
00:28:20,115 --> 00:28:23,961
<i>...wiped out by a series of severe droughts
over the course of a century.</i>

360
00:28:24,786 --> 00:28:27,425
<i>We still carry within
us the echoes of these</i>

361
00:28:27,437 --> 00:28:30,088
<i>extinct civilizations,
in our languages...</i>

362
00:28:30,334 --> 00:28:31,881
<i>...and our myths.</i>

363
00:28:32,127 --> 00:28:35,722
<i>Today, we have a single
global civilization.</i>

364
00:28:35,881 --> 00:28:37,508
<i>How long will it live?</i>

365
00:28:37,674 --> 00:28:41,269
<i>There are so many ways
for a civilization to die.</i>

366
00:28:41,428 --> 00:28:44,648
Let's start with the ones that
we wouldn't be able to do much about.

367
00:28:47,142 --> 00:28:50,772
<i>That supernova is 1000 light-years away.</i>

368
00:28:50,938 --> 00:28:54,988
<i>If it were much closer,
say less than 30 light-years from Earth...</i>

369
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:59,576
...its <i>cosmic radiation would shred
the atmosphere's protective ozone</i> layer...

370
00:28:59,738 --> 00:29:02,116
...and destroy our civilization.

371
00:29:02,282 --> 00:29:05,331
Lucky for us, none of the
stars close enough to harm us...

372
00:29:05,494 --> 00:29:09,499
...are likely to go supernova any time
in the next few hundred million years.

373
00:29:15,462 --> 00:29:19,968
<i>Every million years or so,
a supervolcano erupts somewhere on Earth.</i>

374
00:29:21,009 --> 00:29:24,684
<i>The last time it happened
was 74,000 years ago...</i>

375
00:29:24,846 --> 00:29:28,976
<i>...on the island of Sumatra
in what is now Indonesia.</i>

376
00:29:29,142 --> 00:29:33,648
<i>It spewed hundreds of times more
rock, ash and toxic gas...</i>

377
00:29:33,814 --> 00:29:37,444
<i>...than any single volcano
in recorded history.</i>

378
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:41,955
<i>The molten rock that erupted from
Earth's crust left this caldera...</i>

379
00:29:42,114 --> 00:29:46,711
<i>100 kilometers long, now
filled with</i> a <i>lake.</i>

380
00:29:49,079 --> 00:29:53,585
<i>The Toba volcano sent
more than 600 cubic miles...</i>

381
00:29:53,750 --> 00:29:56,799
<i>...of pulverized rock soaring skyward.</i>

382
00:29:56,962 --> 00:30:00,557
<i>The westward wind
carried the volcanic ash over</i> India...

383
00:30:00,716 --> 00:30:05,267
<i>...where it fell out in a smothering
blanket over the subcontinent.</i>

384
00:30:05,595 --> 00:30:09,441
<i>The eruption loaded the upper atmosphere
with sulfur gases.</i>

385
00:30:09,599 --> 00:30:13,103
<i>The result was a global haze
that blocked most of the sunlight...</i>

386
00:30:13,270 --> 00:30:16,194
<i>...from reaching the surface
for at least five years.</i>

387
00:30:16,356 --> 00:30:20,361
<i>It was like one five-year-long cloudy day.</i>

388
00:30:21,486 --> 00:30:25,161
<i>This so-called volcanic winter
resembled a nuclear winter...</i>

389
00:30:25,324 --> 00:30:27,702
<i>...but without the radiation.</i>

390
00:30:28,910 --> 00:30:30,912
Temperatures fell everywhere.

391
00:30:31,079 --> 00:30:33,753
Plants and animals froze,
even in the tropics...

392
00:30:33,915 --> 00:30:36,043
...dying in enormous numbers.

393
00:30:36,209 --> 00:30:40,089
But life is hardy. Only a few species
were driven to extinction.

394
00:30:40,255 --> 00:30:43,850
One of our ancestors in central India
sharpened this stone blade...

395
00:30:44,009 --> 00:30:46,603
...in the years before the Toba eruption.

396
00:30:47,262 --> 00:30:51,108
And this blade was one of dozens
that were found in the soil layer...

397
00:30:51,266 --> 00:30:53,394
...above the volcanic fallout.

398
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:55,403
This tells us that some toolmakers...

399
00:30:55,562 --> 00:30:58,281
...even in the area
directly affected by the volcano...

400
00:30:58,440 --> 00:31:00,238
...managed to survive the cataclysm.

401
00:31:01,026 --> 00:31:05,452
But the global human population
must have plummeted before rebounding.

402
00:31:05,614 --> 00:31:08,117
If an eruption like this
were to happen tomorrow...

403
00:31:08,283 --> 00:31:10,706
...our civilization would be
brought to its knees...

404
00:31:10,869 --> 00:31:14,248
...although the human species
would survive.

405
00:31:16,833 --> 00:31:20,178
I can imagine that our technology
of a few hundred years from now...

406
00:31:20,337 --> 00:31:23,967
...would allow us to siphon off the energy
of a threatening supervolcano...

407
00:31:24,132 --> 00:31:25,475
...before it explodes.

408
00:31:25,634 --> 00:31:28,478
We could then use that energy
for our own purposes.

409
00:31:28,637 --> 00:31:32,312
About once every million years,
a small asteroid collides with the Earth...

410
00:31:32,474 --> 00:31:35,318
<i>...causing a similar amount of devastation.</i>

411
00:31:35,685 --> 00:31:37,483
<i>With our science and technology...</i>

412
00:31:37,646 --> 00:31:40,320
<i>...we already know how
to prevent an asteroid impact.</i>

413
00:31:40,482 --> 00:31:42,484
<i>We would see it coming years in advance...</i>

414
00:31:42,651 --> 00:31:46,076
<i>...and could send a spacecraft there
to deflect it into a harmless orbit.</i>

415
00:31:46,238 --> 00:31:48,661
With the technology
of a thousand years from now...

416
00:31:48,824 --> 00:31:52,579
...we might even be able to mitigate
the deadly effects of a nearby supernova...

417
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:54,462
...on Earth's atmosphere.

418
00:31:54,621 --> 00:31:58,592
But what happens when
the danger to a civilization is invisible?

419
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:00,673
When no one can see it coming?

420
00:32:09,803 --> 00:32:13,023
TYSON: Beginning with Columbus,
the European invaders of the Americas...

421
00:32:13,181 --> 00:32:17,277
...had a secret weapon
that even they knew nothing about.

422
00:32:17,436 --> 00:32:21,987
<i>They were carrying bacteria and viruses
for deadly diseases, such as smallpox...</i>

423
00:32:22,149 --> 00:32:26,325
<i>...that the original Americans
had never been exposed to.</i>

424
00:32:26,486 --> 00:32:28,625
<i>The Europeans like to
believe that it was their</i>

425
00:32:28,637 --> 00:32:30,787
<i>valor and superior
weapons and culture...</i>

426
00:32:30,949 --> 00:32:32,792
<i>...that won them the New World.</i>

427
00:32:32,951 --> 00:32:36,296
<i>The real conquistadors
were the armies of the pathogens...</i>

428
00:32:36,455 --> 00:32:39,880
<i>...that raced on ahead
to infect and kill nine out of 10...</i>

429
00:32:40,041 --> 00:32:44,296
<i>...of all the Indians of North,
Central and South America.</i>

430
00:32:45,589 --> 00:32:48,263
<i>The great civilizations of the New World
crumbled...</i>

431
00:32:48,425 --> 00:32:51,224
<i>...under the onslaught
of invading microbes.</i>

432
00:32:51,386 --> 00:32:52,979
<i>Without his invisible army...</i>

433
00:32:53,138 --> 00:32:57,939
<i>...Cortez and those who followed
might never have stood a chance.</i>

434
00:32:59,019 --> 00:33:02,398
But what about civilizations
that self-destruct?

435
00:33:10,739 --> 00:33:14,869
<i>Our economic systems were formed
when the planet and its air...</i>

436
00:33:15,035 --> 00:33:19,711
<i>...rivers, oceans, lands,
all seemed infinite.</i>

437
00:33:19,873 --> 00:33:22,968
<i>They evolved
long before we first saw the Earth...</i>

438
00:33:23,126 --> 00:33:26,505
<i>...as the tiny organism
that it actually is.</i>

439
00:33:26,671 --> 00:33:28,218
<i>They're all alike in one respect.</i>

440
00:33:28,381 --> 00:33:32,261
<i>They're profit-driven, and therefore,
focused on short-term gain.</i>

441
00:34:00,247 --> 00:34:04,468
<i>The prevailing economic systems,
no matter what their ideologies...</i>

442
00:34:04,626 --> 00:34:08,301
<i>...have no built-in mechanisms
for protecting our descendants...</i>

443
00:34:08,463 --> 00:34:13,515
<i>...of even 100 years from now,
let alone 100,000.</i>

444
00:34:17,931 --> 00:34:22,152
In one respect, we're ahead
of the people of Ancient Mesopotamia.

445
00:34:22,310 --> 00:34:26,110
Unlike them, we understand
what's happening to our world.

446
00:34:26,565 --> 00:34:29,819
For example, we're pumping
greenhouse gases into our atmosphere...

447
00:34:29,985 --> 00:34:32,488
...at a rate not seen on Earth
for a million years.

448
00:34:33,113 --> 00:34:36,458
And the scientific consensus
that we're destabilizing our climate.

449
00:34:37,158 --> 00:34:40,332
Yet, our civilization seems to be
in the grip of denial...

450
00:34:41,204 --> 00:34:42,831
...a kind of paralysis.

451
00:34:42,998 --> 00:34:47,003
There's a disconnect between
what we know and what we do.

452
00:34:50,714 --> 00:34:53,638
Being able to adapt our behavior
to challenges...

453
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:57,771
...is as good a definition
of intelligence as any I know.

454
00:35:02,100 --> 00:35:05,946
<i>If our greater intelligence
is the hallmark of our species...</i>

455
00:35:06,104 --> 00:35:09,529
<i>...then we should use it,
as all other beings use their advantages...</i>

456
00:35:09,691 --> 00:35:14,197
<i>...to help ensure that their offspring
prosper, and their heredity is passed on...</i>

457
00:35:14,362 --> 00:35:18,868
<i>...and that the fabric of nature
that sustains us is protected.</i>

458
00:35:19,034 --> 00:35:23,835
<i>Human intelligence is imperfect, surely,
and newly arisen.</i>

459
00:35:23,997 --> 00:35:27,422
<i>The ease with which it can be sweet-talked,
overwhelmed, or subverted...</i>

460
00:35:27,584 --> 00:35:29,302
<i>...by other hard-wired tendencies...</i>

461
00:35:29,461 --> 00:35:34,137
<i>...sometimes themselves disguised
as the light of reason, is worrisome.</i>

462
00:35:35,008 --> 00:35:39,229
<i>But if our intelligence is the only edge,
we must learn to use it better.</i>

463
00:35:39,387 --> 00:35:42,891
<i>To sharpen it. To understand
its limitations and deficiencies.</i>

464
00:35:43,642 --> 00:35:46,816
<i>To use it, as cats use
stealth before pouncing.</i>

465
00:35:46,978 --> 00:35:49,401
<i>As walking sticks use camouflage.</i>

466
00:35:50,106 --> 00:35:53,155
<i>To make it the tool of our survival.</i>

467
00:35:53,318 --> 00:35:54,365
<i>If we do this...</i>

468
00:35:54,527 --> 00:35:57,497
<i>...we can solve almost any problem
we are likely to confront...</i>

469
00:35:57,656 --> 00:36:00,830
<i>...in the next 100,000 years.</i>

470
00:36:06,998 --> 00:36:11,094
<i>And now we've arrived at the place
where our ancient dreams of immortality...</i>

471
00:36:11,252 --> 00:36:16,850
...and modern astrophysics converge.
Giant elliptical galaxies...

472
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:19,682
...are something like Florida...

473
00:36:19,844 --> 00:36:23,098
...where the oldest stars
in the universe may be found.

474
00:36:28,728 --> 00:36:33,609
<i>This is a red dwarf star,
smaller and fainter than our sun.</i>

475
00:36:33,775 --> 00:36:37,951
<i>Red dwarfs are by far
the most plentiful stars in the cosmos.</i>

476
00:36:38,113 --> 00:36:42,289
<i>Unlike the sun, which is halfway through
its 10-billion-year lifetime...</i>

477
00:36:42,450 --> 00:36:46,421
<i>...red dwarfs will continue to provide
light and warmth to their planets...</i>

478
00:36:46,579 --> 00:36:48,297
<i>...for trillions of years.</i>

479
00:36:48,456 --> 00:36:52,802
<i>That's hundreds of times longer
than the present age of the universe.</i>

480
00:36:52,961 --> 00:36:54,884
<i>What would intelligent beings do...</i>

481
00:36:55,046 --> 00:37:00,018
<i>...if they had an eternity to develop
their understanding of the universe?</i>

482
00:37:00,176 --> 00:37:04,306
<i>Perhaps they would learn how to open
shortcuts in the fabric of space-time...</i>

483
00:37:04,472 --> 00:37:08,318
<i>...to travel between galaxies
faster than the speed of light.</i>

484
00:37:08,476 --> 00:37:10,979
<i>Maybe they would create
whole new universes...</i>

485
00:37:11,146 --> 00:37:14,241
<i>...as artistic or scientific experiments.</i>

486
00:37:14,399 --> 00:37:17,573
Of course no one,
or at least nobody on Earth...

487
00:37:17,736 --> 00:37:20,865
...knows what the immortals
might do.

488
00:37:21,030 --> 00:37:24,910
<i>If one allows the imagination free rein...</i>

489
00:37:25,410 --> 00:37:26,832
But what about us?

490
00:37:29,998 --> 00:37:32,672
What is our own future?

491
00:37:33,001 --> 00:37:38,508
What would the cosmic calendar
of the next 14 billion years look like?

492
00:37:52,353 --> 00:37:55,698
TYSON: If the original cosmic calendar
includes all of the time...

493
00:37:55,857 --> 00:37:59,031
...from the birth of the universe
until this very moment...

494
00:37:59,194 --> 00:38:04,997
...what would the cosmic calendar look like
for the next 14 billion years?

495
00:38:05,366 --> 00:38:07,869
Just as with the cosmic calendar
of the past...

496
00:38:08,036 --> 00:38:12,291
<i>...every month on the future calendar
equals about a billion years...</i>

497
00:38:12,457 --> 00:38:16,007
<i>...every day, some 40 million.</i>

498
00:38:16,503 --> 00:38:19,382
<i>Science makes it possible
for us to foretell...</i>

499
00:38:19,547 --> 00:38:24,474
<i>...certain astronomical events
in the unimaginably distant future.</i>

500
00:38:24,636 --> 00:38:26,559
<i>The death of the sun, for example.</i>

501
00:38:27,013 --> 00:38:28,936
<i>In some 5 billion years...</i>

502
00:38:29,098 --> 00:38:31,777
<i>...our star will have
exhausted its hydrogen,</i>

503
00:38:31,789 --> 00:38:34,480
<i>the nuclear fuel
that powers it...</i>

504
00:38:34,646 --> 00:38:36,944
<i>...becoming a red giant.</i>

505
00:38:37,106 --> 00:38:40,986
<i>I know that sounds depressing,
but if we apply our intelligence...</i>

506
00:38:41,152 --> 00:38:43,246
<i>...our descendants of
that distant future...</i>

507
00:38:43,404 --> 00:38:47,534
<i>...will have long departed
from the lost worlds of the sun.</i>

508
00:38:47,909 --> 00:38:49,252
<i>Who knows?</i>

509
00:38:49,410 --> 00:38:52,914
Human events entail too many variables,
too many uncertainties...

510
00:38:53,081 --> 00:38:56,051
...to make scientific statements
about our future.

511
00:38:56,209 --> 00:38:58,132
But we can still dream.

512
00:38:58,294 --> 00:39:02,720
The next golden age of human achievement
begins here and now.

513
00:39:03,675 --> 00:39:06,679
<i>New Year's Day of the next cosmic year.</i>

514
00:39:06,845 --> 00:39:08,688
<i>In the first tenth of a second...</i>

515
00:39:08,847 --> 00:39:11,817
<i>...we take the vision
of the pale blue dot to heart...</i>

516
00:39:11,975 --> 00:39:15,696
<i>...and learn how to share this tiny world
with each other.</i>

517
00:39:15,854 --> 00:39:19,404
The last internal combustion engine
is placed in a museum...

518
00:39:19,566 --> 00:39:22,285
...as the effects of climate change
reverse and diminish.

519
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:26,118
<i>A fifth of a second into this future...</i>

520
00:39:26,281 --> 00:39:29,911
<i>...people will stop dying
from the effects of poverty.</i>

521
00:39:30,076 --> 00:39:32,505
<i>The planet is now a completely</i>

522
00:39:32,517 --> 00:39:34,957
<i>self-sustaining,
intercommunicating organism.</i>

523
00:39:35,123 --> 00:39:36,750
<i>A half-second from now...</i>

524
00:39:36,916 --> 00:39:40,762
...the polar ice caps are restored
to the way they were in the 19th century...

525
00:39:40,920 --> 00:39:45,972
<i>...and the forecast is mild and pleasant
for the next cosmic minute and a half...</i>

526
00:39:46,134 --> 00:39:48,887
<i>...40,000 years.</i>

527
00:39:49,721 --> 00:39:54,022
<i>By the time we are ready to settle
even the nearest other planetary systems...</i>

528
00:39:54,183 --> 00:39:56,652
<i>...we will have changed.</i>

529
00:39:57,353 --> 00:40:01,654
<i>The simple passage of so many generations
will have changed us.</i>

530
00:40:01,816 --> 00:40:04,990
<i>Necessity will have changed us.</i>

531
00:40:05,153 --> 00:40:08,748
<i>We are an adaptable species.</i>

532
00:40:09,949 --> 00:40:12,247
<i>It will not be we who
reach Alpha Centauri...</i>

533
00:40:12,410 --> 00:40:15,505
<i>...and the other nearby star systems
on our interstellar arks.</i>

534
00:40:16,581 --> 00:40:19,084
<i>It will be a species very like us...</i>

535
00:40:19,250 --> 00:40:22,971
<i>...but with more of our strengths
and fewer of our weaknesses.</i>

536
00:40:23,129 --> 00:40:27,680
<i>More confident, far-seeing,
capable and wise.</i>

537
00:40:27,842 --> 00:40:31,688
<i>For all our failings,
despite our flaws and limitations...</i>

538
00:40:31,846 --> 00:40:35,476
<i>...we humans are capable of greatness.</i>

539
00:40:36,267 --> 00:40:39,146
<i>What new wonders, undreamt
of in our time...</i>

540
00:40:39,312 --> 00:40:42,942
<i>...will we have accomplished
in another generation...</i>

541
00:40:43,107 --> 00:40:44,825
<i>...and another?</i>

542
00:40:45,860 --> 00:40:48,830
<i>How far will our nomadic species
have wandered...</i>

543
00:40:48,988 --> 00:40:53,915
<i>...by the end of the next century
and the next millennium?</i>

544
00:40:54,786 --> 00:40:56,504
<i>Our remote descendants...</i>

545
00:40:56,663 --> 00:41:01,339
<i>...safely arrayed on many worlds
throughout the solar system and beyond...</i>

546
00:41:01,501 --> 00:41:04,630
<i>...will be unified by
their common heritage...</i>

547
00:41:05,588 --> 00:41:08,057
<i>...by their regard for their home planet...</i>

548
00:41:08,216 --> 00:41:12,062
<i>...and by the knowledge that
whatever other life there may be...</i>

549
00:41:12,220 --> 00:41:17,226
<i>...the only humans in all the universe
came from Earth.</i>

550
00:41:17,850 --> 00:41:22,902
<i>They will gaze up and strain
to find the blue dot in their skies.</i>

551
00:41:23,064 --> 00:41:28,821
<i>They will marvel at how vulnerable the
repository of all our potential once was...</i>

552
00:41:28,987 --> 00:41:34,539
<i>...how perilous our infancy,
how humble our beginnings.</i>

553
00:41:35,576 --> 00:41:39,501
<i>How many rivers we had to cross...</i>

554
00:41:41,541 --> 00:41:44,841
<i>...before we found our way.</i>

